04636nam a22004214a 20180807194000.0m     o  d        cr unu||||||||171201s2017    miu     o      00 0 eng d  a9780472122851  a0472122851q(print)7 a10.3998/mpub.9238370  aMiUbengcMiU  ae-gx--- 4aN6868b.N687 201704a700.41122300aNot Straight from Germany /cMichael Thomas Taylor, Annette Timm, and Rainer Herrn, editors. 1aAnn Arbor [Michigan] :bUniversity of Michigan Press,c[2017]  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 aSocial history, popular culture and politics in Germany  aIssued as part of book collections on Project MUSE.  aIncludes bibliographical references and index.0 aintroduction : sexual publics and sexual citizenship from Hirschfeld to the present / Annette F. Timm -- part one. From the Institute for Sexual Science to PopSex! -- Magnus Hirschfeld's Institute for Sexual Science as archive, museum, and exhibition / Michael Thomas Taylor -- Magnus Hirschfeld's Institute for Sexual Science : a visual sourcebook / Rainer Herrn with Michael Thomas Taylor and Annette F. Timm -- Sexology's beholders : the Exhibition PopSex! in Calgary / Sabine Kriebel -- part two. Sexual publics and popular culture -- Moral panics -- Aroused authorities : state efforts to regulate sex and smut in the German mass media, 1880-1930 / Gary D. Stark -- "Shameful and dangerous women" : sexual promiscuity in World War I Germany / Lisa M. Todd -- Promenading the halls : theaters as sexual spaces in London, Paris, and Berlin around 1900 / Tobias Becker -- Looking through sex -- Anatomy is sublime : the photographic activity of Wilhelm von Gloeden and Magnus Hirschfeld / Kathrin Peters -- Per scientiam ad justitiam : Magnus Hirschfeld's episteme of biological publicity / Kevin S. Amidon -- Of rats and men : rejuvenation and the Steinach film / Rainer Herrn and Christine N. Brinckmann -- Sex in print -- Sentimentalizing the case study : Emma Trosse's deviant genre / Mara Taylor and Michael Thomas Taylor -- Hypermasculine warriors versus effeminate men : masculinity and sexuality in print media by German veterans of the Great War / Jason Crouthamel -- Advertising and Magnus Hirschfeld's commercial legacy in Nazi Germany / Pamela E. Swett -- Consuming sex : a photo-essay on the legacy of Magnus Hirschfeld in the West German erotica industry, 1945-1975 / Elizabeth D. Heineman.  aMagnus Hirschfeld's Institute for Sexual Science was founded in Berlin in 1919 as a place of research, political advocacy, counseling, and public education. Inspired by the world's first gay rights organizations, it was closely allied with other groups fighting for sexual reform and women's rights, and was destroyed in 1933 as the first target of the Nazi book burnings. Not Straight from Germany examines the legacy of that history, combining essays and a lavish array of visual materials. Scholarly essays investigate the ways in which sex became public in early 20th-century Germany, contributing to a growing awareness of Hirschfeld's influence on histories of sexuality while also widening the perspective beyond the lens of identity politics. Two visual sourcebooks and catalog essays on an exhibition of contemporary artists' responses to the Hirschfeld historical materials interrogate the modes of visual representation that Hirschfeld employed by re-imagining the public visibility of his institute from a contemporary perspective. The archival material includes stunning, never-before-published images from Hirschfeld's institute that challenge many received ideas, while the scholarly and art catalog essays explore collaboration and dialogue as methods of research and activism that resonate beyond the academy to pressing issues of public concern.  aDescription based on information from the publisher.10aHirschfeld, Magnus,d1868-1935. 0aArtszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSex in art. 4aElectronic books.1 aHerrn, Rainer,d1957-1 aTimm, Annette F.1 aTaylor, M